pr_body:
# Google Summer of Code 2023 Work Product

These changes are part of my and my mentors @kovzol , @halexus, and Andreas Ebetshuber 's work over three months spanning May (end) 2023 - August (end) 2023. 

## Abstract

With the main objective of adding a web user interface to GNU Aris, this project involved design changes in the GUI and building a Qt-based native application. Consequently, we developed a WebApp based on HTML, Javascript, and WebAssembly.

## Goals Met

- [x] Design Changes
- [x] Build Qt-based Application
- [x] Build WebAssembly Application
- [x] Dark Mode for Qt and WebAssembly versions 

We made most of the design decisions during the Community Bonding Period (May 2023), which I believe was good because deciding upon colors and sizes etc., can lead down a rabbit hole.

For the first half of my project, I mostly worked on the GUI with QML. As a beginner in Qt and QML, I learned a lot as the weeks passed.  I started working on the QML-C++ integration sometime before the mid-semester. 

After mids, I integrated the C++ middle layer with the C logic engine. For this, I used pre-existing source files wherever possible. However, in some cases, I had to write the C logic myself (for example, `goals-qt.c*` , `importProof`) because the source files had it bundled with the gtk implementation. 

Thus, I believe this work can be useful for future implementations (based on platforms other than qt) since now we have a GUI-independent logic engine written purely in C. 

Thus, the Architecture/Design looks somewhat like this:
1. QML-based top-level GUI that communicates key events and data with the C++ layer.
2.  C++ middle layer/wrapper that stores data in `QAbstractListModel` and communicates with both QML and C logic layer.
3. C logic layer that receives proof data (from pointers to `proof_t` and `goal_t` objects) and generates results that are communicated back to the C++ layer. 

Consequently, compilation to WebAssembly (via `emscripten`) was _relatively_ smooth sailing. I used the fusion style for consistency across Desktop and WebAssembly builds.

Also, since WebAssembly is run in a sandboxed environment, native QML FileDialogs were useless. Thankfully, I was able to implement Qt's `QFileDialog::getOpenFileContent` API to get around the problem. As a result, most options (like `Open` , `Import Proof` etc.) have a separate wasm function in the middle C++ layer (that uses the same native function underneath after resolving file I/O). I could have overloaded the same function, but this is more readable.

*Note: It is named with qt, but it doesn't need qt (I named it so because only the qt version ( therefore WebAssembly) uses it)

## Major Problems Faced

During compilation to WebAssembly, I needed clarification about many of the errors thrown. So, (with my mentor's help) I learned about compiling libraries, how dependencies work, etc. We had to compile `libxml2` from source with `emscripten` because it is not originally provided. Again, this made me appreciate the Qt framework even more because most Qt libraries work really well with `emscripten` . In fact, the WebAssembly Kit on Qt Creator has been my go-to after fixing the `libxml2` linking problems. 

Another issue I faced with WebAssembly: adding more `Q_INVOKABLE` methods or `Q_PROPERTY` in the `Connector` class caused `Open` to break. I couldn't find satisfactory solutions anywhere, so as a workaround, I added a new `auxConnector` class for the remaining methods.

While trying to create a Linux `AppImage` , I ran into some `strip` errors with `linuxdeployqt`, strangely enough, it was fixed with  `appimage -n` in the same directory after `linuxdeployqt` failed. Also, since I built it with a fairly recent `glibc` , it ended up being useless. 

## Future Plans

Although original goals have been met, I would like to continue tinkering with Aris on the following (arranged in increasing order of difficulty):

- [ ] Update icons (to improve visibility in dark mode)
- [ ] Make a small how-to-use tutorial
- [ ] Add a SAT Solver
- [ ] Finish Isar Interoperability

## Some ScreenShots

The WebAssembly build:
![image](https://github.com/kovzol/aris/assets/109290910/8e6d9589-18b3-418d-bb2f-a571a3b06398)

The Qt desktop build:
![image](https://github.com/kovzol/aris/assets/109290910/99775684-0dbf-4d24-9910-58613e83b548)

Note: These proofs are taken from `docs/proofs/` . 
## Thanks

I would like to thank everyone involved with the project. It was a great learning opportunity, and I had fun, and I hope this work is useful in classrooms. I thank @kovzol, for always helping me out, and I will miss the weekly meetings.
